You need to use the getFloat() and putFloat() commands in the FloatBuffer of the ByteBuffer. In fact, you should certainly do this simply because of the sheer speed. And it&#39;s a great thing to understand for byte manipulations. You can also mix and match the data, and put and get it as needed. All of it is backed by the byte buffer. So the common happening of sending an array, you need to send the size of the array too.


    public static void writeFloatArray(float[] array, OutputStream stream) throws IOException {
        ByteBuffer buffer = ByteBuffer.allocate(4 * (array.length + 1)).putInt(array.length);
        buffer.asFloatBuffer().put(array,0,array.length);
